### Tuple Structs in Rust

Tuple structs are structs with unnamed fields, accessed by position rather than by name.

---

### Tuple Struct vs Named Struct

| Feature | Named Struct | Tuple Struct |
|---------|--------------|--------------|
| Field access | By name | By position (`.0`, `.1`) |
| Definition | `struct S { x: T, y: U }` | `struct S(T, U)` |
| Destructuring | `S { x, y }` | `S(a, b)` |
| Newtype pattern | N/A | `struct Wrapper(T)` |

---

### Examples

```rust
// Tuple struct
struct Color(u8, u8, u8);
struct Point(f64, f64, f64);

let black = Color(0, 0, 0);
let origin = Point(0.0, 0.0, 0.0);

println!("R: {}, G: {}, B: {}", black.0, black.1, black.2);

// Destructuring
let Color(r, g, b) = black;
println!("RGB({}, {}, {})", r, g, b);

// Newtype pattern - wrap an existing type
struct UserId(i32);
struct ProductId(i32);
// UserId and ProductId are different types, even though both wrap i32
```

> **Key Point:** Tuple structs are useful for creating distinct types from existing types (newtype pattern). This provides type safety by preventing accidental mixing of values that have the same underlying type.

codeExample:
fn main() {
    struct Meters(f64);
    struct Kilograms(f64);

    let distance = Meters(100.0);
    let weight = Kilograms(75.0);

    // distance = weight;  // ERROR: type mismatch!

    println!("Distance: {} meters", distance.0);
    println!("Weight: {} kg", weight.0);
}
